post_cb({"23856316": {"ParentId": "23856294", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>those are line continuations necessary to interpret the whole <code>#define</code> thing as one line, as required by the preprocessor syntax. this way it's just more readable.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "650884", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "23856316", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-05-25T14:28:48.710", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-25T14:28:48.710"}, "23856323": {"ParentId": "23856294", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "2", "Body": "<p>In macro definition, <code>\\</code> means <em>continuation</em>.</p>\n<p>The definition of a macro should be on ONE line, i.e without any break. Since in your definition, the macro definition is so big that it cannot conveniently accommodate on the same line without destroying the readability. So <code>\\</code> is used to indicate to the preprocessor the definition <strong>continues</strong> to the next line so that the program's readability is maintained.</p>\n<p>Note that <code>\\</code> must be followed by a newline. Make sure that there is <strong>no</strong> space after <code>\\</code>.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "415784", "LastEditorUserId": "415784", "LastEditDate": "2014-05-25T14:37:42.837", "Id": "23856323", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2014-05-25T14:29:11.077", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-25T14:37:42.837"}, "23856294": {"CommentCount": "9", "ViewCount": "188", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2014-05-25T21:31:58.123", "LastEditorUserId": "1711796", "CreationDate": "2014-05-25T14:25:51.167", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-25T14:43:11.933", "Title": "What does the '\\' at the end of a #define statement mean?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "23856323", "LastEditDate": "2014-05-25T14:41:57.530", "Id": "23856294", "Score": "-2", "Body": "<p>I saw this code:</p>\n<pre><code>#define REPEAT(statement) \\\n{ \\\n    while((count &amp; ~0x7) &amp;&amp; ((x+8) &lt; width)) \\\n        UNROLL8( statement; count--; x++; ); \\\n    \\\n    while((count &gt; 0) &amp;&amp; (x &lt; width)) \\\n    { \\\n        statement; \\\n        count--; \\\n        x++; \\\n    } \\\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>What is the <code>\\</code> for here?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++>", "OwnerUserId": "2656778", "AnswerCount": "4"}, "23856342": {"ParentId": "23856294", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>The definition of a macro only includes a logical single line. The <code>\\</code> at the end of each line of the macro definition is used to allow the macro definition to be split into multiple physical source lines (presumably for readability reasons).</p>\n<p>This works because a <code>\\</code> followed by a new-line is deleted during phase two of translation, but the preprocessor is run later, in phase four. <code>[lex.phases]/2</code>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_23856294_23856342_0\">Each instance of a backslash character (\\) immediately followed by a new-line character is deleted, splicing physical source lines to form logical source lines.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "485561", "LastEditorUserId": "485561", "LastEditDate": "2014-05-25T14:37:02.820", "Id": "23856342", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2014-05-25T14:31:34.430", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-25T14:37:02.820"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_23856294_23856342_0": {"section_id": 5313, "quality": 1.0, "length": 17}}, "n3337": {"so_23856294_23856342_0": {"section_id": 5110, "quality": 1.0, "length": 17}}, "n4659": {"so_23856294_23856342_0": {"section_id": 6737, "quality": 1.0, "length": 17}}}, "23856322": {"ParentId": "23856294", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>It means that the macro text is continued after the actual line breaks you have.</p>\n<p><code>#define</code> reads its contents from one contigious line. The <code>\\</code> character just <em>'escapes'</em> (i.e. skips) the following line break.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1413395", "LastEditorUserId": "1413395", "LastEditDate": "2014-05-25T14:43:11.933", "Id": "23856322", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-05-25T14:29:09.437", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-25T14:43:11.933"}});